ard questions than to announce that they are to be home-schooled? Of course this doesn't mean that everyone is under suspicion, but you can't expect the government to make exceptions of nice middle-class mums - abuse cuts across all social strata. &#10;There are some educationalists who consider home-schooling to be child abuse in itself, as it prevents vital socialisation and keeps children isolated. I don't think the argument is entirely without merit, so it is right that the proepr authorities ensure that it is a suitable decision in the circumstances. Unsurprisingly, it isn't about the sensibilities of parents, who are often (not always) merely doing what they want without considering their kids' needs or wishes. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1030" language="en" documentId="899" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="speedkermit" date="06 November 2009 3:26pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6744468" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="899" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="555"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="556" end="1030"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>